Euronius: Mr. Meymarakis, welcome to Euronius!
Vangelis Meymarakis: Thank you for the invitation.
Euronius: Nine months ago, your party suffered a crushing defeat by relinquishing to the SYRIZA coalition, but now, according to polls, “New Democracy” has been compared to it in popularity.
What has changed during this time?
Vangelis Meymarakis: Greece has changed, and so have we.
Mr. Tsipras lied a lot in January last year.
Nine months ago, Greece had a surplus of budget and prospects for economic growth.
The country now has a budget deficit and a high level of unemployment.
The investors are gone because Mr. Tsipras has chased them away.
Over the past nine months, the Greeks have had the opportunity to assess the situation in which the country was in January, and the false promises of Mr. Cypriot.
And now they can easily compare what is promised to what has actually happened.
Everyday life has become noticeably worse compared to January, when the situation has improved, and this has affected the majority of Greek citizens.
Euronius: But you say that if you win the election, you will seek alliances with other parties, including SYRIZ.
Vangelis Meymarakis: The thing is, as we have understood in recent years, Greece cannot move forward without understanding and cooperation.
And it is no coincidence that in all other countries where rescue programmes were or are still in operation, the political forces and all the ruling parties gathered together to implement the programme under which they had reached agreement, without giving up their political or ideological autonomy.
That is why I firmly believe that at this stage, only the cooperation of political forces and institutions will allow the country to move forward.
Euronius: Your party voted in favour of the agreement between Mr. Tsipras and the country’s creditors.
If you become the new prime minister on Monday, will you abide by this agreement, or will you try to change it, at least in part?
Vangelis Meymarakis: In fact, we voted in favour of Greece’s move on the European path, because we have a good idea of what the devastating consequences would be for the country’s exit from the EU.
Now Europe is helping us by providing subsidies to our farmers for their products, we have solidarity funds, the Juncker package and assistance in the banking sector.
All this would have been lost if there had not been a treaty with Europe.
But the current austerity measures were the result of Mr. Tsipras negotiating.
I know that Europe does not want to destroy us.
Europe wants to help us.
Thus, if Europe sees that the new Greek government in the first year in power wants to bring order, acts rationally and makes it clear that the country has a strong political will to implement the program of salvation, then, I am sure, the resonance with the resonance with the resonance of the resonance can be.
It would be wrong to believe that in the first year of the new agreement, we will be able to return to negotiations with our creditors, as they expect the agreement to be fully implemented.
If we want to restore their trust, we must continue the privatisation, reforms and structural changes that have been agreed upon, while continuing to take advantage of the benefits of EU funding and the greater investment opportunities that we must open for better understanding and cooperation with Europe.
Unfortunately, in the course of the negotiations, the Cypriot Government did not make any serious arguments on many of the key political issues that we found out by discussing these issues with our European colleagues.
I can give you an example of farmers’ income.
We have explained to our European partners that this is not a fixed monthly income and therefore it cannot be fully taxed in advance.
We were told that the ministers of Cyprus had never spoken about it.
That is, the Greek ministers were unprepared and ill-informed, and therefore failed to negotiate and concluded an unsuccessful agreement.
Euronius: If you win the election, you will soon be at a table with Mr. Juncker, Hollande, Ms. Merkel and other European leaders.
Will what you tell them be different from what your predecessor, Antonis Samaras, told them?
Vangelis Meymarakis: First of all, I will explain to them that by the end of 2014, we were trying to best implement the 2012 agreement, bypassing the sharp corners in it.
We are moving forward with reform.
Of course, we lacked the necessary determination and speed, but we acted in extraordinary circumstances.
The market fell, and there were no potential buyers willing to pay the price set by the Greek government.
I was the speaker of the parliament at the time, I was able to agree on the views of the three parliamentary groups, which at the time constituted a governmental majority.
And despite their serious ideological disagreements over the key bills, we had a functioning parliament, and that was in the presence of populists and extremists, as well as mass demonstrations that took place outside.
And we managed to bring the country to a normal situation that would continue to improve if the process were not interrupted by the early general elections that were the result of the December presidential elections.
Euronius: In recent weeks there has been a massive influx of refugees across Greece.
What do you think about this situation, and the reaction of the European countries that these people aspire to?
Vangelis Meymarakis: The refugee crisis is a slow-acting bomb that we have to deal with after the election victory.
And the reason is that the SYRIZA government did not act in this situation as it should.
In such matters, you should act in advance, because if the problem overtakes you, then only emergency measures remain.
And we're in this situation right now.
Even the interim government that replaced SYRIZ did more in just seven days than Mr. Tsipras did in seven months.
I am sure that these actions of the interim government, to which the President of the Republic, who called for the EU summit, provides valuable assistance, will enable a solution to be found.
We need to see how many refugees will be able to leave the country, and notice that refugees are not illegal immigrants.
They are the victims of the war in Syria, the victims of some extraordinary events that happened to them.
This issue has a deep humanitarian dimension, and we will stick to the position that European politicians must take in this new situation.
The relevant decision must be taken at the EU summit, and the United Nations must also be involved.
We also need better coordination of action, more effective border control and refugee reception centres.
We must also make effective use of the economic assistance we receive from the EU in order to be able to cope with this pressing problem.
Euronius: Mr. Meymarakis, thank you for the interview.
Vangelis Meymarakis: Thank you.
