Sonogenetics allows you to control brain cells by means of sound waves
The video shows how nematodes change the direction of movement when they are exposed to sound pulses.
Scientists have removed worms from a genetically modified nervous system that can be controlled using pulses of sound waves.
Small nematodes change the direction of movement at the moment when they are affected by sound pulses that are too high for the human ear to hear them.
The pulses act by activating neurons that are genetically modified to use membrane channels that respond to ultrasonic waves.
Also on topic: Researchers manage brain activity with the help of light
Scientists have said that worms demonstrate the capabilities of a new technique called "sonogenetics", the essence of which is to use ultrasound to excite certain cells of the brain, heart and muscles, while the source of ultrasound is located outside the body.
Shrikant Chalasani, a research fellow at the Salca Institute, La Hoya, California, told the Guardian that this technique could one day replace deep brain stimulation - an invasive procedure for paralysis that is used to send electrical impulses into the human brain.
Nematodes usually don’t respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that they began to react when placed in a liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
He found that the bubbles amplify the ultrasonic waves, which then penetrate the body of worms.
Enhanced ultrasonic waves affect structures called “TRP-4 ion channels” found in the membranes of some worm cells.
Ultrasonic waves cause these ion channels to open and excite the cells that are associated with them, according to a report in Nature Communications.
To create nematodes that can be controlled by ultrasound, Chalasani made genetic modifications of worms, so their motor neurons used TRP-4 ion channels.
During the use of ultrasound to affect modified organisms, the sound waves were amplified by microscopic bubbles and introduced into the organisms of worms, activating modified motor neurons.
This technique is similar to that applied in "optogenetics" - a new direction that allows scientists to turn on and off neurons by means of light pulses.
Chalasani argues that, compared to this method, sonogenetics may have some advantages.
Unlike light, which is delivered to the required area of the brain via optoelectronic fiber, low-frequency ultrasonic waves pass unhindered through the tissues of the body, so for their delivery it is not necessary to pass inside the skull box.
“We believe that for the treatment of some neurological diseases in clinical conditions the use of gene therapy and therapeutic viruses could temporarily make human neurons sensitive to the ultrasound signal,” Chalasani said.
He added that, in addition, the technique can be applied to muscle and insulin-producing cells.
