In prisons, they are asked to create separate blocks for transgender people.
The Public Council of the Federal Penal Service (FSIN) for the Protection of the Rights of Convicts in October 2015 will discuss, among other issues, the possibility of creating separate blocks in the colonies for transgender and transvestite women.
About this "Izvestiam" told the council member Vladislav Grib.
According to him, depending on the total number of convicted in Russia, not determined by gender, it is possible to provide separate chambers, blocks or even (if there are many such criminals) in domestic prisons in the future to create a special colony for transsexuals.
However, Vladislav Grib emphasizes that it is only possible to determine the punishment of citizens in such isolated places after the convicted persons have undergone appropriate medical examinations, which will prove that the criminal is indeed a person identifying himself as a representative of the opposite sex.
Vladislav Grib is confident that the isolation of transgender people from other prisoners will ensure the safety of the offenders.
According to him, the proposed practice is working successfully abroad: in the CISO (where the defendants are before a court decision) there are separate chambers for transgender people, and in correctional institutions there are special blocks.
Today, this is the only way out of working with such criminals.
They must be unequivocally isolated, since the presence of transvestites and transgender people in ordinary cameras is dangerous for them, it is a suffering for their families and a sea of problems for FSIN staff.
The humiliation of the trans people by the chamberlains is guaranteed, - says Vladislav Grib.
Depending on the size of the city, how many criminals with an undetermined gender, it is necessary to calculate where to distribute them.
There is no need for a separate SIS - only cameras, blocks in prisons.
Yes, a separate colony is possible if there are many transgender people.
According to Mr. Hryb, there may be 50 or 100 people in the block, and if a specialized body is created in Russia alone, the prisoners of transsexuals can go there from any region.
Citizens are included in the CISO at the crime scene, so the admission of transgender women or transgender women from other subjects during the investigation and trial is unrealistic, but to introduce such a practice for those already convicted in a separate colony - yes, - says Mr. Grib.
Recall that the day before, law enforcement officials were unable to decide in which investigative isolationist - male or female - to identify the drug-detained 24-year-old transgender Dmitry Kozhukov (known as Alina Davis) was a non-resident.
He was released from his home on a no-show.
This news has been widely discussed in social networks and media, as the mechanism of transgender content in SISO and colonies in Russia really does not yet exist.
The Russian human rights defender, activist of the LGBT movement (LGBT - lesbians, gays, bisexuals, transsexuals) Nikolai Alexeev supported the idea of creating special places to dispense with the punishment of their own transgender people, noting that it is also possible to define people in a colony abroad.
Given the atmosphere in Russian prisons, the proposal is right.
Yes, this is a very small percentage, but the problem exists, as well as the issue of security in prisons for homosexuals, - says Alexeyev.
Prisons should be safe, so individual blocks could be made for this and for homosexuals, especially since there are more of them in prisons than transgender ones.
At the same time, Alexeyev doubts that there will be many citizens in Russia ready to pretend to be transsexuals in order to get into a colony different from the usual.
Of course, you can introduce a medical examination before placing people in a transgender colony, but not always everything happens unambiguously.
For example, in the United States, one of the inmates Chelsea Manning looked like a man, and already in prison stated that he wanted to change the gender, - said Alexeyev.
A person can feel anything they want.
But while there are no specific places to punish transgender people, I doubt that prison officials will take the safety of such people seriously and delve into the subtlety of their orientation or gender identity.
At the same time, the international expert on reproductive health in the territory of the Russian Federation Boris Lordkipanidze noted that the introduction of a new system of distribution of transgender criminals in the colony can greatly delay the beginning of the sentence of convicts.
A commission is created - it is a matter of sexology, psychiatrists carry out long-term observations, it is not a single test, on the basis of which a high-precision conclusion is made.
Today’s psychiatry capabilities allow for this.
Therefore, even before a gender change, potential patients always undergo such examinations – they accurately show whether a gender change with surgical intervention is the necessary measure,” says Lordkipanidze.
However, it is difficult for me to imagine how to implement this system in relation to the convicted, since it takes an average of one month for such an examination.
The doctor, despite the fact that in general the idea of creating separate blocks for transgender people was supported, also doubts that in the current economic conditions it will be appropriate to allocate funds for the construction of new premises, medical examinations, - transgender units in Russia.
It is difficult to calculate, there are no official statistics, but if you consider that homosexuals in Russia are about 5%, then you can say that transgender people are even less, and those who have such a deviation and even commit crimes, quite a small number.
Now, at the request of the colony administration, homosexuals, transgender people can obtain separate conditions of detention.
Mikhail Antipov won the Junior World Chess Championship.
In Khanty-Mansiysk, the World Chess Championship was completed among juniors under the age of 20.
The end of the championship seemed more than intriguing.
The winner was determined only in the last round, and they became the Russian Mikhail Antipov, who still managed to force the Pole Jan-Kshishtof Dudu, who would seem confident to go to the title.
Ukrainian chess player Natalia Buksa celebrated the victory in the girls.
The World Chess Championship, which took place from the beginning of September in Khanty-Mansiysk, already in the middle of the tournament distance, seemed to lose almost all intrigue, as the representative of Poland turveyed in the system Jan-Kshishtof Duda, who issued a series of four victories.
Given that Duda was a ranking favorite of the primacy, and is generally considered to be one of the most promising young chess players, the probability that he would miss the resulting break was very negligible.
And even when Duda slowed down the turnover and allowed the Russian Mikhail Antipova to reduce the lag to only 0.5 points, he remained an obvious favorite in the fight for the title.
After all, Antipov had to win in the 13th round to reach the leader.
But even that wouldn't help if you won the Dude's game.
Plus, this obligation to win could, of course, affect the game of the Russian chess player and lead to non-obligatory mistakes.
Fortunately, Mikhail Antipov managed to avoid them.
He had to deal with Francesco Rambaldi, after which he was forced to wait for Duda to finish his game, who met with Benjamin Bok.
Luckily for Antipov, a Polish chess player brought a confrontation with a Dutch insider.
Thus, Antipov and Duda scored an equal number of points - by 10 out of 13 possible, but Antipov had the best additional scores.
That is why it is the leadership of the Khanty-Mansiysk Autonomous District, whose governor Natalya Komarova, traditionally paying great attention to the development of chess in the region, awarded the main prize.
But in the competitions of the girls of an intriguing ending did not happen.
The leader of the tournament - Natalie Bukse (Ukraine) - to win the title was enough not to lose in the last round, which she successfully did.
Thus, the victory of the Russian Alina Bivol did not allow her to reach Buksa.
The Russian athlete remained second with a lag of the champion in 0.5 points.
