Kyiv has broken the nuclear union.
Kiev formally announced Ukraine’s refusal to cooperate with Russia on the completion of the Khmelnytskyi nuclear power plant.
The Supreme Council on Wednesday, with a second attempt, nevertheless voted in favour of the dissolution of the agreement with Moscow.
The agreements for the construction of the third and fourth blocks were signed in 2010-2012, but the implementation of the project was never successful.
On Wednesday, the Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine adopted a law that dissolves the agreement concluded in 2010-2012 with the Russian Federation on the construction of the third and fourth block at the Khmelnytskyi nuclear power plant.
The bill passed by the country's government was only successful from the second vote, for the first time it was supported by 210 MPs with the necessary minimum of 226, but then 234 MPs voted in favour of the bill.
The Khmelnytsky nuclear power plant established under the USSR on the original project was to have four 1 GW power units with VVER-type reactors, but only two were able to be built.
Negotiations with Moscow on reconstruction led to the conclusion of an intergovernmental agreement by 2010, and in 2011-2012 the Council adopted the relevant laws.
Since there were no funds in the budget of Ukraine, it was assumed that building blocks would have to be on loan from the Russian side, but the funds were never allocated.
After the coup in Kiev in February 2014 and the subsequent cooling in relations between the two countries, Kiev began to twist relations with Moscow in the nuclear industry, announcing the refusal to cooperate on the Khmelnytskyi nuclear power plant and on the construction project in Ukraine.
The only area in which relations have been maintained is the purchases in the Russian Federation of fuel for the existing Ukrainian nuclear power plants (provided about half of the electricity production in the country), since so far the Ukrainian NAEK "Energoatom" replace Russian supplies with nothing.
The plans to build the Khmelnytskyi nuclear power plant with another contractor in Ukraine have not yet been definitively abandoned: in 2014, negotiations with the Czech Skoda JS were announced in Kiev.
