There have been clashes between migrants and police on the Hungarian border.
Refugees staged protests on the Serbian border near the Hungarian town of Reske, which have turned into clashes with law enforcement.
As a result, Hungarian police used water bottles and tear gas, according to Reuters.
The migrants throw stones at the police and try to take down the fence on the border.
The site of the clashes is being reinforced, police take action in response to aggressive actions by migrants and their attempts to breach the border.
According to Agence France-Presse, the refugees managed to break through the police border, after which dozens of migrants fled to the territory of Hungary.
Some refugees are leaving the Serbian-Hungarian border on buses to Belgrade and the border with Croatia, the BBC reports.
The authorities of the country allowed the migrants to arrive in Croatian territory and ensure their transportation from there to the desired country.
According to the Hungarian authorities, 20 police officers were injured.
On September 15, the Hungarian Parliament tightened the legislation on migration and border protection.
The amendments include the participation of the army in the protection of state borders, the criminal prosecution of those who illegally cross the border, as well as an accelerated procedure for the examination of asylum requests.
The Hungarian court has already found one migrant guilty of illegally crossing the Hungarian-Serbian border, in connection with which he will be deported and will not be able to return to Hungary within one year.
In the near future, the Hungarian Parliament also intends to consider the transfer of border protection functions to the Hungarian Armed Forces of the country’s parliament.
At the end of June, Hungarian authorities began construction of a 175 km long barbed wire fence on the border with Serbia to curb the flow of migrants and refugees into the country.
The Russian admitted to committing the largest cyberattack in U.S. history.
Indicted in the largest cyber attack in U.S. history, Russian Vladimir Drinkman has confessed to stealing more than 160 million credit card numbers, Reuters reports.
During the trial in the federal court of New Jersey, Drunkman confessed to a conspiracy to gain unauthorized access to computer systems and to commit fraud.
