The total damages from the actions of the accused were estimated at $300 million.
“The defendants, such as Vladimir Drinkman, who have the skills to hack into our computer networks, pose a threat to our economic well-being, privacy and national security,” U.S. Attorney Paul Fishman said in a statement.
Drinkman faces 30 years in prison, as well as a million-dollar fine.
When issuing a sentence, the court will take into account the recognition of the Russian and may reduce the time limit for him.
Drinkman's sentence will be announced on January 15.
Vladimir Drinkman was arrested in the Netherlands in 2012.
At the same time, another suspect Dmitry Smilianets was taken into custody.
The latter denies his guilt in the crimes he is charged with.
