Four people were killed when police opened fire with rubber bullets on protesters in Nepal
Four people, including a 4-year-old boy, were killed in southern Nepal when police began firing rubber bullets at a crowd protesting against the country's proposed new constitution, the official said on Wednesday.
The violence took place on Tuesday evening in Rupandea County, about 175 miles west of Kathmandu, the country’s capital.
Bishnu Prasad Dakal, the district police chief, said more than 1,000 protesters gathered at one of the police stations, some throwing stones and fire bombs.
Mr. Dakal reported that the police used tear gas, then fired into the air before launching rubber bullets.
Twenty police officers and five civilians were injured, he said.
It is not clear why rubber bullets, which are known to kill, but are traditionally used as a less deadly alternative, have caused such high mortality.
The clash was the last in weeks of fierce protests in southern, flat Nepal, where representatives of the Madési people say the new provinces formed under the new constitution will diminish their political influence.
The protests also took place in western Nepal, among Tara nationalities who want to have their own state.
At least 40 people, including eleven police officers, have been killed in violent clashes, starting with 10
In August, when the four main political parties signed an agreement to divide the country into a province, it became a decisive step on the way to a new constitution, but a very controversial issue in Nepal, which was centrally ruled for several centuries.
Work on the new constitution has been underway since 2008, but lawmakers have accelerated the process after the devastating earthquake that killed thousands of people in April.
Legislators voted in favour of the draft constitution in Kathmandu this week, and officials said the new chapter would be signed by Sunday.
