Google launches a campaign to double donations to raise $11 million for refugees
Google Inc (GOOGL.O) has announced the start of a doubling of donations campaign to raise $11 million for humanitarian organizations to help displaced European countries refugees fleeing war-torn and impoverished countries.
Google has used an uncharacteristic personal approach, announcing a campaign to collect donations on its blog.
Instead of making a statement by one of the executives, Google employee Rita Masud, who had fled Kabul with her family when she was seven, described her personal experience.
“We got on dubious trains and buses, endured hunger, thirst, cold and fear,” she wrote.
I'm lucky.
But as the refugee and migrant crisis in Europe has escalated, so many people like my family desperately need help.
The donations will be donated to four non-profit organizations dedicated to helping refugees and migrants: Doctors Without Borders, the International Rescue Committee, Save the Children and the Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees.
Google has said it will double the first $5.5 million in donations until the amount on the google.com/refugeerelief page reaches $11 million.
Europe is facing the strongest refugee crisis since World War II, triggered by the majority of the four-year civil war in Syria, which has displaced more than 4 million people this year.
Many are also fleeing war-torn Afghanistan, Yemen, Iraq and Libya.
