Diabetics with low obesity may be able to help obesity surgery.
The beneficial effect after obesity surgery in people with low obesity who suffer from type 2 diabetes can last for at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is still too early to claim that diabetics with low obesity live longer after obesity surgery than those who receive non-surgical treatment.
“The mortality statistics aren’t showing up right away,” said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in obesity surgery, who wrote about the new study in the column of the editor of JAMA Surgery.
Obesity surgery, or bariatric surgery, uses various methods to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the ability of organisms to absorb food.
For several years, bariatric surgery has proven its effectiveness in treating type 2 diabetes, but major studies have been conducted among people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
The BMI, a measure of weight relative to growth, is considered normal at 18.5 to 24.9.
BMI 25 or above indicates that a person is overweight and people with BMI above 30 are considered obese people.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery – gastric shunting and arm gastrectomy, with medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in non-men.
The mean BMI of those who had undergone surgery dropped from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year of their participation in the study.
At the same time, the BMI of those who received non-surgical treatment for diabetes remains at about level 29.
Among those who underwent surgery, 36% fully recovered from diabetes, and partly - 28%.
In the group that received medication, for comparison, complete cure of diabetes was observed only in 1%, and partial - only about 2%.
In addition, indicators of blood pressure, triglycerides and “bad” LDL cholesterol “were generally better in the surgical group,” the authors say.
The researchers also monitored levels of hemoglobin A1s in the blood, which reflect blood sugar levels in dynamics.
Hemoglobin A1c is best kept below 7%, the researchers write.
After surgery, the average level of hemoglobin A1c decreased from about 9% to about 6%.
In the therapeutic group, however, it remained stable, at about 8%.
But the best glycemic control indicators reflected by good levels of hemoglobin A1c did not reduce mortality over five years, according to the head of the study, Dr. Chi-Cheng Su and colleagues.
The research group also compared the average results of two types of surgical treatment.
For the fifth year, compared to the group who had a half-shoulder gastrectomy, the shunting group lost more weight (18.7 kg versus 14.2 kg), achieved a greater reduction in BMI (by 7.4 versus 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c by 9% (by 3.1% versus 2.1%), and also had a greater decrease in sex.
Although the new study does not demonstrate the benefits of the surgical method in terms of life expectancy after five years, there is evidence from the results of a study of people with excess body weight in Sweden that surgical treatment of the ulterior flexo actually leads to an increase in life expectancy, according to Blackstone.
According to a Swedish study for people with obesity who chose bariatric intervention, the probability of dying over 15 years was approximately 29% lower compared to the group who used more traditional methods.
Although the new study did not show an increase in life expectancy, Blackstone noted that it encourages people with a BMI below 35 who are interested in such a procedure.
“Here the report is very important because it states that such a surgical intervention is safe in a group with low BMI, where there is no increased risk of mortality or kidney disease,” she said.
Blackstone added that people and their doctors should start taking weight seriously as soon as a patient’s BMI reaches the range between 27 and 30.
“I think we’re waiting too long to get people to take it seriously,” she said.
It seems to me that once they accumulate the genetic changes that trigger obesity and diabetes in their bodies, it is very difficult to reverse it.
