News Economics <0xE2><0x80><0x95> Nobel laureate: Globalization
The process of globalization should have helped to reduce inequalities in the world.
In fact, the situation looks different, the difference in income of the population in the developing economies, on the contrary, is growing.
Eric Muskin.
To correct this, it is necessary to increase the level of education of low-skilled workers, according to the chief researcher of the International Laboratory for Analysis and Decision-Choosing of the NIU HSE, winner of the 2007 Nobel Prize in Economics Erik Maskin.
In the last twenty years, the world has experienced an unprecedented growth in global markets.
The trade borders between the two countries have become more and more open.
Proponents of globalization have predicted great benefits for developing economies.
“These predictions have come true in many ways,” Muskin said.
For example, China and India have seen a significant increase in GDP per capita.
However, not all is so joyful.
It was expected that globalization would reduce the gap between the “poor” and the “unpoor” in poor countries, which manifests itself in large income inequality, or rather in wages.
But in reality, this inequality has only increased, notes Eric Muskin in his article “Why global markets have not reduced inequality in emerging economies,” published in The World Bank Economic Review, which has been translated and quoted by NIE BSE.
Together with economist Michael Kremer, a professor at Harvard University, Eric Muskin has developed an alternative theory that demonstrates why income disparities in poor countries are increasing as globalization grows, according to NIE WSE.
Specific processes are taking place in the new global market.
To demonstrate them, Maskin sets out four levels of professional qualifications – A and B for rich countries, C and D – for poor countries.
After globalization, D specialists from poor countries lack the level of qualifications to cooperate with A and B specialists from rich countries.
And if C-level workers from poor countries have a higher salary thanks to cooperation with B-level employees from the rich, then D-level workers do not feel growth or their salaries are falling at all.
The resulting effect is that internationalization of production will contribute to increasing the pay gap between the two categories of specialists in poor countries and, accordingly, to increasing the level of inequality.
Kremer and E. Maskin proposed an astonishingly beautiful model, an alternative to the Ricardian theory of comparative advantages.
It makes it possible to explain why globalization has led to income inequality, - says Fuad Alesserov, an ordinary professor, head of the International Laboratory for Analysis and Choice of Solutions, head of the Department of Mathematics of the University of Economics.
And like any powerful theory, I'm sure it will lead to a burst of empirical work in this field.
According to Eric Maskin, the solution to the problem is to increase the level of education of low-skilled workers.
However, the workers themselves, as the scientist notes, do not have the funds for this, and companies are not profitable to pay for their training.
In such a situation, governments, international agencies, NGOs and private funds can play a significant role, Muskin said.
The scientist notes that the theory developed does not in any way call for a halt to the process of globalization, which has brought about and is bearing fruit in the form of the growth of countries’ GDP.
