The U.S. Embassy regrets the closure of the American Center in Moscow.
The U.S. Embassy in Russia has expressed its regret at the closure of the U.S. Center’s foreign literature library.
The center has worked in Moscow for more than 22 years.
The U.S. Embassy in Moscow deeply regrets the unilateral decision of the Russian government to close the U.S. Embassy Center at the All-Russian State Library of M.I. Rudomino in Moscow.
"The unilateral steps taken by the Russian Federation in recent times call into question the commitment of the Russian government to the relations between the Russian and American peoples, which were not interrupted even during the Cold War and in other difficult moments of the U.S.'s long history of relations."
The American Center has established deep and strong links between the people and the culture of Russia and the United States.
It was the center of American culture, history and literature in the Russian capital, and also served as a meeting place with numerous prominent American figures, including astronauts, artists, athletes, scientists, politicians, and writers.
“Last year alone, the American Center held more than 400 cultural and educational events and welcomed more than 50,000 Russian visitors,” the diplomat said.
Tefft recalled that about a year ago it was decided to close another Russian-American joint project – the FLEX (Future Leaders Exchange Program).
The Green Tribunal was quick to dissolve.
Typical situation: Four officials stand at the table of Judge Swantaner Kumar, hearing his claims about the work done.
The court is completely dissatisfied with the quality of your work.
We have not given you a 110-page order so that you may rejoice over it,” Kumar said.
If at least one more brick is laid, we will order to remove all existing buildings.
Kumar is headed by the National Green Tribunal (NZT), a judiciary body established in 2010 to stop the rapid pollution of the environment that has accompanied the rapid economic growth of recent decades.
During this time, the Tribunal was able to consider more than 10,000 claims related to air pollution, garbage collection, geological developments, toxic waste and the construction of dams.
In two out of three cases, the court decides to stop the construction leading to pollution.
The rates are incredibly high: in less than 60 years since the declaration of the independence of industrial development, India has turned from a country of the virgin jungle into one of the most overpopulated and polluted countries in the world.
Particularly acute is the problem in large metropolises, where the development of infrastructure does not follow the rapid urbanization: cities are covered with dense smog, rivers are filled with pesticides and waste snails of enterprises and households.
Despite the formal support of the green movement by the state, the NZT is regularly criticized by Narendra Modi’s government, as it often becomes the main reason for the cancellation of major investment projects.
In May of this year, the environment minister called the court’s decisions “extreme” and “unenforceable”.
Sometimes it is really impossible to enforce the court’s decisions within the time limit set by the court, confirms environmental lawyer Raj Panjvani.
However, unfulfilled deadlines also have a positive side: at least they make the responsible persons move.
“His main goal is to shake up this system,” the lawyer adds.
The Green Tribunal has repeatedly cancelled large constructions: at its expense, the construction of the airport, power plant and hundreds of smaller buildings.
At the same time, people are also trying to remember: for example, during the discussion of the fate of a pharmaceutical company in the state of Telagnana, which polluted the local river with fluoride.
We can close your factory, but we are also responsible for the economic consequences.
“People will lose their jobs,” Kumar commented on his decision.
However, such explanations are not always understood by ordinary people, whose lives can be changed by a single pencil.
So, in April, the Tribunal decided to ban all vehicles older than 10 years from entering the capital, which caused public outrage.
Despite a sharp decline in popularity and a plethora of criticism, Swatanter Kumar refused to cancel the decision.
Instead, he ordered the Delhi government with statistics on inbound and outbound road transport, and also offered to purchase 10,000 additional buses, after knowing in advance at factories whether they were able to carry out such an order.
As sources of pollution such as landfills, fuel quality and even road accidents began to fall into the attention of the courts, the anger of the people began to calm down a bit.
But the most painful theme of the principle judge was the program to clean the Ganges, with a pump announced by Prime Minister Narendra Modi last year.
When it comes to the Ganges - a river sacred to the Hindus, the judge often stops holding back his emotions and goes on to scream.
Do you know what the word "holy" means?
Someone poured water out of the Ganga on the statue of God, and it contained feces, - the judge is hot.
You keep polluting the river because you think: Ganges are Ganges, he will take away all our sins.
This is a river that we worship, and see what you do with it every day.
The Ganges Cleanup is the most ambitious and costly environmental project announced by the new government.
Currently, the number of faecal bacteria in this river exceeds the norm more than 120 times.
Every year, between 1.5 and 3 out of 700 million Hindus bathing in it die from infectious diseases.
In February, Narendra Modi even donated money to the Ganga Rescue Fund from the sale of his suit, in which he met with Barack Obama and 455 other items from his personal collection.
Ecologists immediately accused the prime minister of populism: the suit was bought for $700,000, while cleaning the river requires at least eight billion.
Supporters of the Green Tribunal agree that India must go a long way before it can call itself a developed country, but do not believe that the cost of progress should be ecology.
“In a developing country, environmental conversations are often perceived as unacceptable luxury,” said Malika Bhanot, an activist at Call Ganga.
And the court is trying to find a golden middle ground between ecology and development.”
